---
import "../../styles/homepage.css";
import "../../styles/puzzlequests.css";
const year = new Date().getFullYear();
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Puzzle Quests &mdash; The Lions Alliance</title>
    <meta name="description" content="Puzzle Quests is a family of three hand-built heritage walking experiences by The Lions Alliance — designed in partnership with regional museums and brought to life with bespoke physical props." />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
  </head>
  <body class="tla-page pl-body">

    <!-- ── Navigation ─────────────────────────────────── -->
    <nav class="tla-nav" id="tla-nav">
      <div class="tla-nav__inner tla-container">
        <a href="/" class="tla-nav__logo">The Lions <span>Alliance</span></a>
        <ul class="tla-nav__links">
          <li><a href="#overview">Overview</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pilot">Meijel Pilot</a></li>
          <li><a href="#quests">The Quests</a></li>
          <li><a href="#adapt">For Your Venue</a></li>
          <li><a href="#collaborate">Collaborate</a></li>
        </ul>
        <a href="/" class="tla-nav__cta">&larr; Back to Studio</a>
        <button class="tla-nav__hamburger" id="hamburger" aria-label="Toggle menu">
          <span></span><span></span><span></span>
        </button>
      </div>
      <div class="tla-nav__mobile" id="mobile-menu">
        <a href="#overview">Overview</a>
        <a href="#pilot">Meijel Pilot</a>
        <a href="#quests">The Quests</a>
        <a href="#adapt">For Your Venue</a>
        <a href="#collaborate">Collaborate</a>
        <a href="/">&larr; Back to Studio</a>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <!-- ── Hero ───────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-hero" id="home">
      <div class="tla-container pl-hero__inner">
        <div class="pl-hero__text tla-fade">
          <div class="pl-hero__breadcrumb">
            <a href="/">The Lions Alliance</a>
            <span class="pl-hero__breadcrumb-sep">/</span>
            <span>Experiences Pillar</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-hero__badges">
            <span class="tla-badge tla-badge--dev">In Development</span>
            <span class="tla-badge tla-badge--live">Heritage Pilot 2026</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="pl-hero__title">Puzzle <em>Quests</em></h1>
          <p class="pl-hero__subtitle">
            Three hand-built walking experiences for museums and heritage venues. Each one weaves a local legend into a route through the landscape &mdash; carried in the visitor&rsquo;s hands by a bespoke physical prop. No app, no screen, no host required. The kit ships ready to play and resets in under five minutes between groups.
          </p>
          <div class="pl-hero__ctas">
            <a href="#collaborate" class="tla-btn tla-btn--gold">Bring this to your venue</a>
            <a href="#quests" class="tla-btn tla-btn--outline">See the three quests &darr;</a>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-hero__visual tla-fade tla-d1">
          <figure class="pl-sketch pl-sketch--hero">
            <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/Hero_StudioOverview.png" alt="Studio sketchbook frontispiece — three Puzzle Quests presented at a glance: Skeleton Key, Living Chronicle, and Puzzle Lantern, with a small Peel landscape and the Museum Medelo route." loading="eager" />
          </figure>
          <span class="pl-sketch__caption">Studio frontispiece &mdash; three wandelingen, &eacute;&eacute;n Peellandschap</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── The Concept ────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-overview" id="overview">
      <div class="tla-container pl-overview__inner">
        <div class="pl-overview__text tla-fade">
          <span class="tla-overline">The concept</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header pl-section-header--left">A heritage story, walked through the landscape that holds it</h2>
          <p>
            Puzzle Quests is a family of three hand-built walking experiences. Each starts and ends at the partner museum&rsquo;s reception desk and follows a route through the surrounding village, peatland, or heritage site. As the visitor walks, the prop in their hands responds to the world around them &mdash; lighting up, vibrating, writing itself, illuminating hidden details.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each quest is built around a specific local legend or archival story. The story is the spine of the experience; the prop is the way the visitor enters it. We design everything from the ground up: the narrative, the prop, the route, the booklet, the puzzle, the on-site stations, the staff briefing at the museum desk.
          </p>
          <p>
            The first three instances are being designed and built for <strong>Museum Medelo in Meijel</strong>, in partnership with Heemkundevereniging Medelo. The hardware, the puzzle frameworks, and the operational model are designed for replication &mdash; once the Meijel pilot proves the format, the same props adapt to other regional museums and heritage venues with a story-research effort measured in tens of hours, not years.
          </p>
          <div class="pl-tags">
            <span class="pl-tag">Museums &amp; heritage</span>
            <span class="pl-tag">Local-legend storytelling</span>
            <span class="pl-tag">Walking routes</span>
            <span class="pl-tag">School programmes</span>
            <span class="pl-tag">Revenue-share model</span>
            <span class="pl-tag">No app, no host</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-overview__visual tla-fade tla-d1">
          <figure class="pl-sketch">
            <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/Concept_WorkingDesk.png" alt="Studio working-desk sketchbook page showing the archive folder from Heemkundevereniging Medelo, a researcher's hand writing, three prop-design sheets stacked at the corner, and a process timeline from archive to museum desk." loading="lazy" />
          </figure>
          <span class="pl-sketch__caption">Working desk &mdash; from het Medelo-archief to a walked route</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="tla-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── Meijel Pilot ───────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-pilot" id="pilot">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">First pilot</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">Museum Medelo, Meijel</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-pilot__grid">
          <div class="pl-pilot__text tla-fade">
            <p>
              The first three Puzzle Quests are being designed and built in partnership with <strong>Heemkundevereniging Medelo</strong> &mdash; the local-history society that runs Museum Medelo at Tomveld 2 in Meijel. Each quest is rooted in a real archival story from the Medelo collection: a flight from Prussian recruiters in the 1730s, the life of a Belgian vagrant who walked the Peel for forty years, and a Roman legionary&rsquo;s remains found in the peat near the Meijel&ndash;Sevenum road.
            </p>
            <p>
              The Medelo partnership gives us three things at once: archival depth that makes each story credible, a starting venue where visitors pick up the kit and return to a stamp at the end, and an operating track record that supports approaching other regional museums (Limburgs Museum, Streekmuseum De Locht, and the fortified-town partners across Brabant and Limburg).
            </p>
            <p>
              Our goal for 2026 is to take the first quest from prop prototype to live museum operation. The other two follow on the validated kit and operational pattern.
            </p>
          </div>
          <ul class="pl-pilot__facts tla-fade tla-d1">
            <li><span class="pl-pilot__label">Venue</span><span class="pl-pilot__value">Museum Medelo, Tomveld 2, Meijel</span></li>
            <li><span class="pl-pilot__label">Heritage partner</span><span class="pl-pilot__value">Heemkundevereniging Medelo</span></li>
            <li><span class="pl-pilot__label">First quest live</span><span class="pl-pilot__value">Target late 2026</span></li>
            <li><span class="pl-pilot__label">Format</span><span class="pl-pilot__value">Walking route, 45&ndash;95 min, return to museum desk</span></li>
            <li><span class="pl-pilot__label">Audiences</span><span class="pl-pilot__value">Family visits &middot; school groups (90&ndash;120 min) &middot; couples</span></li>
            <li><span class="pl-pilot__label">Operating model</span><span class="pl-pilot__value">Revenue-share with the host museum</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="tla-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── How It Works ───────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-steps-section" id="how-it-works">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">How it works</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">The visitor journey, in three beats</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-steps">
          <div class="pl-step tla-fade">
            <div class="pl-step__number">I</div>
            <div class="pl-step__title">Collect the kit</div>
            <div class="pl-step__desc">At the museum desk: a prop, a booklet, a route notesheet, and a short briefing in the story. No app, no screen, no setup.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-step tla-fade tla-d1">
            <div class="pl-step__number">II</div>
            <div class="pl-step__title">Walk the route</div>
            <div class="pl-step__desc">The route runs through the village and surrounding landscape. The prop responds at every station &mdash; through lock, page, or lantern &mdash; revealing one more piece of the story.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-step tla-fade tla-d2">
            <div class="pl-step__number">III</div>
            <div class="pl-step__title">Return to the desk</div>
            <div class="pl-step__desc">Visitors return with a completed booklet and the prop lit up with their progress. Staff verify, stamp the notesheet, and use the conversation to share an extra archival detail. The kit resets in under five minutes for the next group.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── The Three Quests ───────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-quests" id="quests">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">The quests</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">Three quests. Three props. Three local legends.</h2>
        </div>

        <!-- ── Skeleton Key ──────────────────────────── -->
        <article class="pl-quest pl-quest--key tla-fade" id="quest-key">
          <div class="pl-quest__visual">
            <figure class="pl-sketch">
              <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/SkeletonKey.png" alt="Sketchbook design page of the Skeleton Key prop — ornate brass lion's-head bow, translucent shaft with eight hidden Peelschrift runes, heraldic bit." loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <span class="pl-sketch__caption">The Skeleton Key &mdash; design page V</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-quest__body">
            <div class="pl-quest__eyebrow">Quest I &middot; Skeleton Key</div>
            <h3 class="pl-quest__title">De Vlucht door de Peel</h3>
            <p class="pl-quest__story">
              Between 1713 and 1740, Prussian King Frederick Wilhelm I sent recruiters across the border to collect exceptionally tall young men for his elite Riesengarde. The men who fled used a secret network of safe-houses through the Peel. Those who made it to Meijel were free &mdash; they settled, married, and had tall children. This is documented as the reason Meijel has historically more tall men than its neighbouring villages.
            </p>
            <p>
              The Skeleton Key is the warden&rsquo;s master pass. Eight genuine lock-stations &mdash; hidden in tree trunks, mossy stones, and trail-posts along the route &mdash; each carry one letter of the keyword <strong>VRIJHEID</strong> (Freedom). The key senses each next station via radio proximity, pulsing harder as the walker closes in. At each lock the key is physically turned, an NFC-scan triggers, and one of the runes along the shaft glows softly through the aged brass. By the final lock all eight runes are lit. The walker speaks the keyword aloud at the museum desk &mdash; that is their proof of passage.
            </p>
            <ul class="pl-quest__chips">
              <li><span>Difficulty</span><strong>&#9733;&#9733;&#9733;&#9734;</strong></li>
              <li><span>Duration</span><strong>75&ndash;95 min</strong></li>
              <li><span>Distance</span><strong>~5 km</strong></li>
              <li><span>Group</span><strong>2&ndash;6</strong></li>
              <li><span>Age</span><strong>10+</strong></li>
              <li><span>Mechanic</span><strong>Chain of locks &middot; radio proximity &middot; 8-letter word</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="pl-quest pl-quest--key-stations tla-fade tla-d1">
          <div class="pl-quest__visual pl-quest__visual--wide">
            <figure class="pl-sketch">
              <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/SkeletonKey_Stations.png" alt="Three lock-station archetypes for the Skeleton Key quest — tree trunk, mossy stone, and Dutch trail-post — each hiding a keyhole with reactive vein-lighting." loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <span class="pl-sketch__caption">Lock-station archetypes &mdash; tree-trunk, stone, trail-post; invisible to passers-by, alive to the key</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-quest__body pl-quest__body--narrow">
            <p>
              Stations are designed to disappear into the landscape. A casual passer-by walks past them without noticing &mdash; only the visitor carrying the key sees the hidden veins of light begin to pulse as they close in. Three archetypes distribute across the route: cast bark on a real tree, a Jesmonite-cast glacial-erratic stone, and a Dutch recreational trail-post. One additional station &mdash; the recruiter&rsquo;s decoy &mdash; lures rushed players who ignore the colour chain.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <div class="pl-quest-divider" aria-hidden="true">&middot; &middot; &middot;</div>

        <!-- ── Living Chronicle ──────────────────────── -->
        <article class="pl-quest pl-quest--chronicle pl-quest--reverse tla-fade" id="quest-chronicle">
          <div class="pl-quest__visual">
            <figure class="pl-sketch">
              <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/LivingChronicle.png" alt="Sketchbook design page of the Living Chronicle prop — a forest-green leather grimoire with embossed tree-and-bog cover and seven flexible e-paper pages that fill in as the walker progresses." loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <span class="pl-sketch__caption">The Living Chronicle &mdash; design page III</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-quest__body">
            <div class="pl-quest__eyebrow">Quest II &middot; Living Chronicle</div>
            <h3 class="pl-quest__title">Het Pad van Dikke Mie</h3>
            <p class="pl-quest__story">
              Anna Marie Mommaerts &mdash; known as <em>Dikke Mie</em> &mdash; was born in Lummen in 1711. She lived as a vagrant through the Peel region for forty years, repeatedly arrested, whipped, and exiled for begging. Despite official prohibition, farmers in Meijel quietly gave her food and shelter in their barns. She passed through Meijel many times. In June 1755, she was found dead in a barn on the Donk. The church register noted only: <em>&lsquo;een zwerfster&rsquo;</em> &mdash; a vagrant woman. This is not a supernatural legend. It is a human life the world chose to forget.
            </p>
            <p>
              The Chronicle is a leather-bound tome with a tree-and-bog motif embossed on the cover and the title in Peelschrift glyphs &mdash; an invented alphabet used across all three quests. Inside are seven flexible e-paper pages, all blank at the start except for one inscription: <em>&ldquo;Loop de cirkels. Ik zal schrijven wat ik mij herinner.&rdquo;</em> At each Magic Circle along the route, the walker places the closed book on the engraved disk. The book trembles, the spine glows faintly, and a new page writes itself. By the end of the walk the visitor holds a complete hand-walked chronicle of a forgotten life.
            </p>
            <ul class="pl-quest__chips">
              <li><span>Difficulty</span><strong>&#9733;&#9733;&#9734;&#9734;</strong></li>
              <li><span>Duration</span><strong>45&ndash;60 min</strong></li>
              <li><span>Distance</span><strong>~2 km</strong></li>
              <li><span>Group</span><strong>1&ndash;4</strong></li>
              <li><span>Age</span><strong>14+</strong></li>
              <li><span>Mechanic</span><strong>Memorial walk &middot; seven self-writing pages &middot; comprehension at the desk</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <div class="pl-quest-divider" aria-hidden="true">&middot; &middot; &middot;</div>

        <!-- ── Puzzle Lantern ────────────────────────── -->
        <article class="pl-quest pl-quest--lantern tla-fade" id="quest-lantern">
          <div class="pl-quest__visual">
            <figure class="pl-sketch">
              <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/Lantern.png" alt="Sketchbook design page of the Puzzle Lantern prop — a four-sided verdigris green-bronze Victorian-style lantern with ornate roof, dormer UV window, brass handle and four legs." loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <span class="pl-sketch__caption">The Puzzle Lantern &mdash; design page VI</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-quest__body">
            <div class="pl-quest__eyebrow">Quest III &middot; Puzzle Lantern</div>
            <h3 class="pl-quest__title">De Schat van het Dolle Moer</h3>
            <p class="pl-quest__story">
              A thieving knight rode from the Maaskant across the Peel to raid the peat-farmers&rsquo; village. The farmers drove him off. In his panicked night flight across the Dolle Moer, he and his squire sank into the bog with their stolen gold and the knight&rsquo;s golden sword. His spirit now haunts the road between Meijel and Sevenum &mdash; in mist and rain, his cries lure travellers off the path. The legend is rooted in real archaeology: 4th-century Roman finds &mdash; a silver helmet and Constantine-era coins &mdash; were documented from the peat near the Meijel&ndash;Sevenum road in the 1970s.
            </p>
            <p>
              The Puzzle Lantern is a four-sided verdigris green-bronze Victorian-style lantern with leaded glass-in-lead panels, a dormer UV window in the ornate roof, and a brass carrying handle. The visitor sets the lantern down on top of each station post; the lantern reads the post by NFC and lights its LED ring with a coordinate (count &times; direction) the walker decodes against the journal in their other hand.
            </p>
            <ul class="pl-quest__chips">
              <li><span>Difficulty</span><strong>&#9733;&#9733;&#9733;&#9733;</strong></li>
              <li><span>Duration</span><strong>60&ndash;90 min</strong></li>
              <li><span>Distance</span><strong>~3&ndash;4 km</strong></li>
              <li><span>Group</span><strong>2&ndash;8</strong></li>
              <li><span>Age</span><strong>10+</strong></li>
              <li><span>Mechanic</span><strong>Lantern + journal &middot; UV reveal &middot; fold + overlay puzzles</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="pl-quest pl-quest--lantern-journal pl-quest--reverse tla-fade tla-d1">
          <div class="pl-quest__visual">
            <figure class="pl-sketch">
              <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/Lantern_Journal.png" alt="Studio sketchbook page showing the Codex / Journal of Johannes van Leliëndaal — thirteen pages with varied puzzle interactions including UV reveal, fold-to-align, vellum overlay, die-cut window, and dry-erase verification." loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <span class="pl-sketch__caption">The Journal &mdash; <em>Het Journaal van Johannes van Leli&euml;ndaal</em>, thirteen pages with varied puzzle interactions</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-quest__body">
            <h4 class="pl-quest__subtitle">The Journal carries the puzzle</h4>
            <p>
              The lantern is the scanning instrument. The puzzle itself lives in a thirteen-page leather-bound journal in the style of an EXIT-game booklet from Kosmos / 999 Games &mdash; rebranded in-world as the field journal of a fictional 1742 surveyor who mapped the Dolle Moer and vanished before completing his work. Pages reveal hidden symbols under the lantern&rsquo;s dormer UV beam, fold along marked lines to align Peelschrift glyphs, layer with translucent vellum to reveal hidden paths, and verify the final answer via a lift-flap.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="pl-quest pl-quest--lantern-stations tla-fade tla-d2">
          <div class="pl-quest__visual pl-quest__visual--wide">
            <figure class="pl-sketch">
              <img src="/images/puzzle-quests/Lantern_Stations.png" alt="Seven station tableaux for the Puzzle Lantern quest — waist-height oak posts with brass NFC discs on top, alongside atmospheric antique items: horseshoe, oil lamp, cracked mirror, framed Roman coin, silver candlestick, oval brass frame." loading="lazy" />
            </figure>
            <span class="pl-sketch__caption">Lantern stations &mdash; waist-height oak posts and atmospheric thrift-store antiques, one tableau per legend beat</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-quest__body pl-quest__body--narrow">
            <p>
              Lantern stations are openly placed and visible &mdash; this is a deliberate puzzle, not a search-and-find. Each station pairs a waist-height oak post (the visitor sets the lantern on top to scan) with one atmospheric antique sourced from local thrift shops &mdash; a horseshoe, an oil lamp, a cracked mirror, a brass-framed Roman coin replica, a tarnished silver candlestick, an oval brass frame. The antiques don&rsquo;t carry the puzzle &mdash; they carry the character of each story-beat.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Adapt for your venue ───────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-adapt" id="adapt">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">For your venue</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">The hardware is reusable. The story is the work.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-adapt__grid">
          <div class="pl-adapt__col tla-fade">
            <h3 class="pl-adapt__title">What stays fixed</h3>
            <ul class="pl-adapt__list">
              <li>The prop hardware &mdash; we build it once and re-use it across instances.</li>
              <li>The puzzle frameworks (chain navigation, memorial page-reveal, lantern coordinate decode).</li>
              <li>The operating model &mdash; pickup at desk, walk the route, return to desk for the stamp and conversation.</li>
              <li>The technical platform &mdash; NFC, radio proximity, e-paper, UV-reveal.</li>
              <li>The five-minute kit reset between groups.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-adapt__col tla-fade tla-d1">
            <h3 class="pl-adapt__title">What we design per venue</h3>
            <ul class="pl-adapt__list">
              <li>The story &mdash; researched from your archive, written for the route.</li>
              <li>Illustrations, booklet content, and any cipher tied to your venue.</li>
              <li>The route &mdash; scouted on-site, station placement, length, walking grade.</li>
              <li>Station object aesthetics adapted to your landscape (cast iron beam, stone, bronze plaque, etc.).</li>
              <li>Staff briefing for the desk conversation at return.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="pl-adapt__effort">
              Adaptation effort per quest: <strong>20&ndash;50 hours of design work</strong>, depending on the quest type. The prop hardware is reused as-is; only engraved details, paint colourways, firmware constants, and content are venue-specific.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Development Status ─────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-development" id="status">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">Where we are</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">Development status</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-phase-grid">
          <div class="pl-phase-card pl-phase-card--done tla-fade">
            <div class="pl-phase-card__number">01</div>
            <div class="pl-phase-card__title">Story research, prop &amp; route design</div>
            <span class="pl-phase-card__badge">Complete</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-phase-card pl-phase-card--active tla-fade tla-d1">
            <div class="pl-phase-card__number">02</div>
            <div class="pl-phase-card__title">Visual design &amp; build guides</div>
            <span class="pl-phase-card__badge">In Progress</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-phase-card pl-phase-card--upcoming tla-fade tla-d2">
            <div class="pl-phase-card__number">03</div>
            <div class="pl-phase-card__title">First-prop fabrication &amp; live Meijel pilot</div>
            <span class="pl-phase-card__badge">Late 2026</span>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-phase-card pl-phase-card--future tla-fade tla-d3">
            <div class="pl-phase-card__number">04</div>
            <div class="pl-phase-card__title">Second venue partnerships</div>
            <span class="pl-phase-card__badge">2027</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Our Thinking ───────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-philosophy">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">Our thinking</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">Why we are building this</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-philosophy__grid">
          <div class="pl-philosophy__card tla-fade">
            <span class="pl-philosophy__card-icon">&#9995;</span>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-title">Tactile over purely digital</div>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-desc">Real physical interaction creates moments that screens cannot replicate &mdash; weight, light, vibration, and the surprise of an object that responds to you become part of the story.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-philosophy__card tla-fade tla-d1">
            <span class="pl-philosophy__card-icon">&#129309;</span>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-title">Heritage as living material</div>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-desc">Local archives hold stories that no screen can do justice to. We work directly with the heritage society of each venue to ensure the legend on the page is the legend that was actually walked.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-philosophy__card tla-fade tla-d2">
            <span class="pl-philosophy__card-icon">&#127761;</span>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-title">Atmosphere as a design material</div>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-desc">Light, weight, sound, and the timing of a reveal are deliberate tools. Each prop is engineered to feel like it belongs in the century where the story takes place.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-philosophy__card tla-fade tla-d3">
            <span class="pl-philosophy__card-icon">&#127759;</span>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-title">The desk conversation matters</div>
            <div class="pl-philosophy__card-desc">Every quest ends with the visitor returning to the museum desk for a stamp. We design that conversation: staff are briefed not just to check answers, but to share one more archival detail. That conversation is the highest-value moment a museum has with each visitor.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Collaboration CTA ──────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-collaborate" id="collaborate">
      <div class="tla-container pl-collaborate__inner">
        <div class="pl-collaborate__text tla-fade">
          <span class="tla-overline">Partnership</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header pl-section-header--left">Bring a Puzzle Quest to your museum</h2>
          <p>
            We&rsquo;re looking for the next two or three regional museums and heritage venues to deploy Puzzle Quests after the Meijel pilot completes. If you have a local story that deserves to be walked &mdash; a forgotten figure, a documented escape, an archaeological find, a folk legend with a real archival trace &mdash; we&rsquo;d love to hear from you.
          </p>
          <p>
            The model is a revenue-share on net ticket revenue, with the museum hosting the kit, the briefing, and the return conversation. We handle story research, prop adaptation, route scouting, on-site testing, and staff training. The first conversation is usually a visit to your venue, an hour with your archivist, and a walk of one possible route.
          </p>
          <div class="pl-collaborate__ctas">
            <a href="mailto:hello@thelionsalliance.com" class="tla-btn tla-btn--gold">Get in touch</a>
            <a href="/" class="tla-btn tla-btn--outline">Explore the studio &rarr;</a>
