    <!-- ── FAQ ────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pl-faq">
      <div class="tla-container">
        <div class="tla-fade" style="text-align:center;">
          <span class="tla-overline">FAQ</span>
          <h2 class="tla-section-header">Common questions from museum partners</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="pl-faq__list">
          <div class="pl-faq__item tla-fade">
            <div class="pl-faq__question">How does the operating model work in practice?</div>
            <div class="pl-faq__answer">Visitors purchase the quest at the museum reception (we suggest &euro;8&ndash;15 per student for school programmes, scaled for families and adults). The museum keeps a 30&ndash;40% share of net ticket revenue. The kit is reusable and resets in under five minutes between groups. Staff need a short briefing per quest to handle the return-desk conversation; we provide that briefing as part of the launch.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-faq__item tla-fade tla-d1">
            <div class="pl-faq__question">What does adapting a quest to our venue actually involve?</div>
            <div class="pl-faq__answer">The hardware is reused unchanged. The custom work per venue is: story research (with your archivist), narrative writing, illustration, station-object aesthetics adapted to your landscape, route scouting, and staff briefing. Effort ranges from 20 to 50 hours of design work per quest, depending on which of the three you start with. We start with one quest, validate the operation, then add the others as the partnership grows.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-faq__item tla-fade tla-d2">
            <div class="pl-faq__question">Do visitors need a smartphone or an app?</div>
            <div class="pl-faq__answer">No. Every quest is fully self-contained in the physical prop and booklet. The prop has its own NFC reader, e-paper, lighting, and audio &mdash; the visitor&rsquo;s phone stays in their pocket the entire walk.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-faq__item tla-fade tla-d3">
            <div class="pl-faq__question">How does it handle weather?</div>
            <div class="pl-faq__answer">Props are designed for Peel weather &mdash; sealed leather covers, waterproof page materials, exterior-grade varnishes on station objects. Acceptable exposure is light rain and mist. For prolonged downpour or freezing conditions, the quest can be paused at the museum&rsquo;s discretion.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="pl-faq__item tla-fade">
            <div class="pl-faq__question">When can we book a pilot for our venue?</div>
            <div class="pl-faq__answer">The Meijel pilot is the first live deployment, targeted for late 2026. Second-venue conversations begin in parallel; the first new-venue rollout would realistically be 2027. Early conversations now are how we shape the next year of work &mdash; the earlier we know your story, the sooner it can become a quest.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

